\begin_layout Title
Leveraging ICT to provide agricultural advice to smallholder farmers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout, David J Spielman and Els Lecoutere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Agricultural advisory services generally rely on interpersonal knowledge
 transfer, involving agricultural extension officers visiting farmers individual
ly or in groups.
 This approach is not always cost-effective and has often proved hard to
 bring to scale.
 Information and Communication Technologies have been advanced as a promising
 way to strengthen agricultural extension services.
 We test the effectiveness of three ICT-mediated models to transfer agricultural
 extension information.
 First, we investigate the effectiveness of video as means to transfer informati
on, increase technology adoption, increase productivity and improve well-being.
 Furthermore, we quantify the additional impact of augmenting video with
 Interactive Voice Response (IVR) technology—a more demand-driven approach
 to information provision.
 Finally, we measure the additional effect of sms reminders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With new possibilities offered by information and communications technology
 (ICT), an abundance of pilot projects and commercial products have entered
 the market with a focus on revitalizing agricultural extension in developing
 countries.
 However, a growing body of evidence suggests that not all ICT-mediated
 extension approaches are equally effective in achieving outcomes such as
 increased knowledge and awareness, higher rates of technology adoption,
 better crop yields, and eventually improvements in household welfare.
 This may be because, as has been found in information campaigns more generally,
 seemingly small design attributes—the way information is delivered, who
 delivers the information, and who was targeted—can significantly influence
 these outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper investigates the effectiveness of an ICT-enabled extension approach
 designed to provide information about improved maize cultivation practices
 to smallholder farmers in Uganda.
 We consider the specific ICTs through which the information is delivered
 to the farmer, and differentiate between (i) short audiovisual messages
 viewed on tablet computers that provide detailed information on improved
 maize cultivation; (ii) interactive voice response (IVR) systems that farms
 call into if the need for additional information arises; and (iii) short
 message service (SMS) that nudge farmers at particular points in time about
 key farming practices they should apply.
 The outcomes used to assess the relative effectiveness of these different
 ICTs include increases in knowledge about improved maize cultivation by
 the subject farmer; and changes in household-level indicators such as the
 use of improved inputs, technologies, and practices; farm production and
 disposal; and well-being.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We draw on a field experiment in which farmers were randomly assigned to
 a group that received a particular ICT-mediated information interventions,
 and were then compared to a group that did not receive that particular
 information intervention 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2016field"

\end_inset

.
 We work with almost 4,000 farm households sampled from the population of
 households cultivating maize across five districts of eastern Uganda.
 The core information intervention takes the form of a short video that
 explains simple yet effective ways to increase maize productivity and profitabi
lity, such as recommended practices in row spacing, the importance of quality
 seed, optimal soil fertility management, and farm budget management.
 To test the overall effectiveness of the information provided through the
 video medium, we compare outcomes of farmers who were exposed to a placebo
 video to outcomes of farmers who were shown the informational video.
 In addition, we provided access to an IVR system to about two-thirds of
 the sampled households who were shown the informational video and, within
 that group, we sent about half of the sampled households a series of eight
 follow-up SMS messages at strategic points in time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farm household level, we find that providing information to farmers
 through short video messages increases their knowledge about modern inputs,
 improved technologies, and recommended practices.
 In addition, farmers who were shown the video are also more likely to adopt
 a range of inputs, technologies, and practices that were presented in the
 videos.
 We also find clear effects on production with maize yields 14 percent higher
 than in control households.
 However, these results do not translate into greater well-being.
 We also find that the IVR generates no additional impact on knowledge,
 nor does it have a strong influence on technology adoption: we only find
 a positive effect of IVR on the uptake of hybrid seed.
 Still, we do find that households that were allocated to the IVR treatment
 report yields that are 8 percent higher.
 We also find no effect from the SMS service.
\end_layout

