Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a world characterized by incomplete and asymmetric information, and intra-hou
sehold gender related constraints to efficiency, targeted efforts to fill
 knowledge gaps can make a big difference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2011poor,udry1996gender"

\end_inset

.
 However, not every information campaign is equally effective nor inclusive,
 and often, seemingly small attributes, such as the way it is delivered,
 who is targeted by the message and who delivers the message, can result
 in significant differences in impact at the household and intra-household
 level.
 Understanding and quantifying the importance of each of these design attributes
 through rigorous evaluation research should therefore be an essential part
 of any knowledge exchange model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we evaluate the effectiveness of three complementary ICT-enabled
 agricultural extension approaches (short video messages, IVR, and SMS)
 that can be brought to scale relatively easily and at significantly lower
 cost than alternative modes of agricultural extension.
 In addition, and motivated by the observation that most agricultural extension
 advisory services are biased toward men, we assess the impact of two gender-rel
ated attributes of our ICT-enabled extension approach.
 The first attribute cvaries the gender composition of the person or persons
 that provide the information.
 The second attribute varies the gender composition of the person or persons
 to whom the information is targeted.
 This allows us to test three hypotheses related to (1) the overall effectivenes
s of the information intervention (2) the role of information asymmetries
 within the household; and (3) the effectiveness of cooperative approach
 to farming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The various hypotheses are tested using a field experiment where the messenger
 of the information and the recipient of the information is randomly altered
 according to a 3 by 3 factorial design.
 The study population was maize farm households in Eastern Uganda, from
 which we sampled about 3,600 couples.
 These farmers were shown a video according to the treatment group they
 were randomly assigned to.
 The videos showed how improved technologies and practices can be used to
 increase production and introduced.the concept of inter-temporal decision-making
 in farm enterprise management.
 The messages were packaged in an attractive and accessible manner, and
 featured role-model farmers explaining how intensification of maize production
 improved their lives.
 The videos were shown twice, once just before the the planting season,
 and once during planting stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that as a result of being shown the video, farmers have experienced
 improvements in several key knowledge outcomes.
 We do not find incremental effects for the addition of IVR and SMS reminders.
 As a result of being shown the video, farmers also adopted a range of recommend
ed practices: in particular, wefind that farmers reduced their use of DAP
 or NPK and increased their use of urea (and to a lesser extent inorganic
 fertilizer), thereby managing their soils in a more balanced manner.
 Effects are less strong when IVR was added to the video treatment.
 However, there is some evidence that a demand-driven information service
 such as IVR may be more effective to increase the adoption of more complex
 technologies (eg.
 basal application of DAP and the use of hybrid maize seed).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a result of having been shown a video, households reduce the area under
 maize cultivation while producing the same amount, leading to a significant
 increase in maize yields, from 428 kg/acre to 488 kg/acre.
 Adding IVR further increases this to 526 kg/acre, but this is driven by
 an increase in production on the same area under cultivation.
 We find no effect from any intervention on self assessed well-being, nor
 on consumption expenditures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is some evidence to suggest that showing video only to the female
 co-head reduces household-level knowledge outcomes as opposed to when the
 information is given to the man only.
 There is also some evidence that targeting the couple instead of only the
 man leads to an increase in the likelihood of using inorganic fertilizer
 and that this fertilizer is also combined with improved seed.
 Comparing male-recipient households to households where the video was shown
 to the couple results in no differences in production-related outcomes
 measured at the household level.
 Changing the messenger attribute does not have any effect on household-level
 outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the video is shown to the couple or the woman in the household (as
 opposed to showing it to only the man), knowledge of the woman increases
 significantly, suggesting information does not flow from the man to the
 woman within the household.
 When the video was shown to couple (as opposed to only the man), women
 are more likely to speak up if they do not agree, and it is more likely
 that an agreement is reached.
 If women also receive the information (alone or as part of the couple),
 men are less likely to make adoption decisions unilaterally.
 If women also receive information, they will make significantly more decisions
 on the use of improved agronomic practices and inputs, but only if this
 information is not also available to the husband.
 Showing the video to both spouses jointly does seem to increase the likelihood
 of joint decision making for some practices, but none is significant after
 correcting for multiple comparisons.
 Finally, on an average plot of one acre, if the video was shown to a woman
 only, the amount produced per acre under male management reduces by 34
 kg and the amount under female management increases by about 26 kg.
 We do not find that it matters if the information in the video was provided
 by a man, a woman, or a man and woman together.
 
\end_layout

